But when you combine the two, there are none better than San Antonio’s adopted son ... more Image 52 of 52 NBA releases video of Tim Duncan's first 20-point game 1 / 52 Back to Gallery Tim Duncan has risen, laced up his size 16 kicks and dropped at least 20 points in a game 775 times throughout his NBA career.
The NBA has been Duncan's playground for 18 seasons going on 19, but there was a time, believe it or not, when Duncan was new to the park.
He hadn't been given free reign on the equipment yet. Back in 1997, the older boys still believed it was their own, that no kid — regardless of where he came from or what he did before — could just walk in and claim it.
He had to prove himself to join the club.
It didn't take long for the kid from the Virgin Islands to make it known that the land, the equipment, the jungle gym and the seesaw and everything in-between, belonged to him.
Now, the NBA has provided us a glimpse into the past by releasing a video of Duncan's first ever 20-point game.
It didn't take the 21-year-old long to establish himself as a force.
On Nov. 11, 1997 — Duncan's seventh game as a pro — the No. 1 overall pick broke through the 20-point barrier for the first time, scoring 22 points against the Timberwolves.
One down, 776 to go.
The video is a reminder both of what Duncan was immediately capable of and how he has evolved as time has (sort of) caught up.
Young Duncan's ability to get off the floor so quickly is remarkable for a man of his stature.
RELATED: Photo of young Tim Duncan, Chris Paul featured by SI Vault
Age has transformed Duncan into a more plodding figure in recent years, but his first-step used to be a nightmare for opposing bigs. On one dunk in the video, his defender, Cherokee Parks is still trying to reconcile what just happened while Duncan is flying in for a two-handed slam.
And he's already showcasing the genius post footwork he'd come to be known for in the coming years. Duncan is just a rookie here, but he's already duping defenders with shimmies and shuffles and head fakes ripped straight from Kevin McHale's all-time reel.
Just days away from his 19th season, Duncan is far removed from that recent college grad we see in the video, but you can see the line, can see how he got from then to now .
And even now, all these years later, the playground is still his.
